  "response_text": "The average number of livestock destocked begins at zero at the start of the simulation. A sharp increase occurs by the third time step, reaching a maximum of 6.6144. This initial spike reflects an immediate imbalance between the initial herd size and available pasture resources, necessitating rapid removal of animals to prevent overgrazing. Following this peak, the metric exhibits a volatile but consistent downward trajectory. Secondary peaks occur at time step 9 with a value of 3.3733 and at time step 12 with 2.7406, indicating lingering adjustments in herd management. By time step 27, the number of destocked animals drops to a valley of 0.5083, suggesting that households have largely adapted their stocking rates to the ecological carrying capacity.\n\nA significant shift in dynamics occurs around time step 30, after which the trend stabilizes with periods of no significant change interspersed with minor fluctuations. Towards the conclusion of the simulation at time step 100, the average destocking level settles at 0.3111. Although a slight increasing trend is observed between time steps 66 and 76, likely driven by climatic variability and risk sensitivity, the overall system demonstrates a long-term reduction in resource-induced livestock loss as agents adjust their strategies."
}

